---
/**
 * Where should I form my business? — hub page.
 *
 * The worked example below is computed at BUILD TIME by the same function the
 * island calls, so the prose and the calculator cannot drift apart. Every
 * dollar figure on this page comes from that call or from the formation
 * dataset; none is typed into the copy.
 *
 * Copy marked data-review="legal" is legal-adjacent and wants a human read
 * before this page is indexed. Two things are deliberately NOT asserted
 * anywhere here, because the research came back empty on both: the legitimate
 * non-tax reasons for Delaware incorporation, and whether Wyoming or Nevada
 * anonymity survives the Corporate Transparency Act.
 */
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import FormationComparisonCalculator from '../../components/calculators/FormationComparisonCalculator.tsx';
import { compareFormationStates, rankByFiveYear, AGENT_TIERS } from '../../lib/formation-compare';
import { formatMoney } from '../../lib/tax-engine';
import { states } from '../../data/states';

// The worked example from the specification, computed rather than written.
const example = compareFormationStates({
  homeState: 'OH', workState: 'OH', entity: 'llc',
  annualRevenue: 150_000, annualProfit: 110_000,
  ownerSalary: 0, ownerDistributions: 110_000,
  numberOfOwners: 1, numberOfEmployees: 0,
  agentTier: 'standard', filingStatus: 'single',
});
const exRanked = rankByFiveYear(example);
const oh = example.columns.find((c) => c.state === 'OH')!;
const wy = example.columns.find((c) => c.state === 'WY')!;
const de = example.columns.find((c) => c.state === 'DE')!;
const wyExtra = wy.fiveYearTotal - oh.fiveYearTotal;
---

<Base
  title="Where should I form my business? State comparison calculator (2026)"
  description="Compare what it costs to form and run an LLC or corporation in every state for 2026 — including the foreign registration you still owe where you actually operate."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="hero-label">2026 tax year</p>
    <h1>Where should I form my business?</h1>
    <p class="tagline">Forming out of state usually adds cost. This shows you how much.</p>
  </section>

  <div class="callout" data-review="legal">
    <strong>Before you read the numbers</strong>
    <p>
      Forming in Wyoming, Delaware or Nevada does not remove tax or registration obligations in the state
      where your business actually operates. An out-of-state entity doing business in its owner's state
      must usually register there as a foreign entity and pay that state's taxes anyway.
    </p>
    <p>
      That is not a caveat on the calculation below. It <em>is</em> the calculation: every out-of-state
      column keeps your operating state's obligations and adds its own on top.
    </p>
  </div>

  <p>
    The advice to form in Wyoming or Delaware is everywhere, and for a business that physically operates
    somewhere else it is usually wrong on cost. You do not replace your home state's requirements by
    filing elsewhere — you acquire a second set. Two annual reports, two registered agents, two states
    that can dissolve you for missing a deadline.
  </p>

  <h2>The worked example</h2>
  <p>
    An Ohio consultant running an LLC on {formatMoney(150000)} of revenue and {formatMoney(110000)} of
    profit, comparing Ohio against the states people are usually told to use:
  </p>

  <table class="data-table">
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Form in</th><th>Formation</th><th>Foreign registration in Ohio</th><th>Annual</th><th>Five-year total</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      {exRanked.slice(0, 5).map((c) => (
        <tr class={c.isOperatingState ? 'total' : undefined}>
          <td>{c.stateName}{c.isOperatingState ? ' — where the work happens' : ''}</td>
          <td>{c.formationFee.amount === null ? '—' : formatMoney(c.formationFee.amount)}</td>
          <td>{c.foreignRegistration.oneTime === null ? '—' : formatMoney(c.foreignRegistration.oneTime)}</td>
          <td>{formatMoney(c.annualTotal)}</td>
          <td>{formatMoney(c.fiveYearTotal)}</td>
        </tr>
      ))}
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p>
    <strong>Wyoming costs {formatMoney(wyExtra)} more than Ohio over five years</strong>, not less. Delaware
    costs {formatMoney(de.fiveYearTotal - oh.fiveYearTotal)} more. The Wyoming filing fee really is cheaper
    than Ohio's — and it does not matter, because the Ohio obligations do not go away.
  </p>

  <div class="callout" data-review="legal">
    <strong>Your income tax does not move either</strong>
    <p>
      Pass-through income is taxed where the owner lives and where the income is earned — not where the
      LLC is filed. In this example the federal bill is {formatMoney(example.federal.tax)} and the Ohio
      income tax is {formatMoney(oh.stateIncomeTax)}, and both are identical in every column above.
    </p>
    <p>
      This is what kills the "move my LLC to Florida" idea for a California resident. The LLC can be
      filed anywhere; the owner still lives in California, and California still taxes them.
    </p>
  </div>

  <p class="section-label">Run it on your own numbers</p>
  <FormationComparisonCalculator client:load />

  <h2>What an LLC actually is, for tax</h2>
  <p data-review="legal">
    An LLC is created under state law. Its federal tax treatment depends on the entity's tax
    classification — disregarded, partnership, S corporation or C corporation — and not on the state it
    was formed in. Changing the state of formation does not change federal tax at all. That is why the
    federal figure above sits outside the comparison table rather than inside it.
  </p>

  <h2>What this does not include</h2>
  <p>
    Everything below is real and none of it is in the totals. A calculator that quietly omits costs is
    worse than one that names them:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Sales tax and economic nexus.</strong> Selling into a state can create obligations there. This site has no sales tax dataset and does not compute any part of it.</li>
    <li><strong>Property tax.</strong> Not modeled anywhere on this site.</li>
    <li><strong>Local business licenses</strong> — city and county registrations, which vary enormously and are not held in any dataset here.</li>
    <li><strong>Attorney and formation-service fees.</strong> Only the state's own charges are counted.</li>
    <li><strong>Federal beneficial ownership reporting.</strong> No figure is included for it.</li>
    <li><strong>Fee changes.</strong> The five-year projection holds today's fees flat. It applies no inflation and predicts no increases, though states do raise them — Louisiana's rise in October 2026 is already known.</li>
    <li><strong>Registered agent pricing</strong> is a typical market range ({formatMoney(AGENT_TIERS.basic.cost)} to {formatMoney(AGENT_TIERS.premium.cost)} a year), not an official fee.</li>
    <li><strong>Costs marked "unquantified"</strong> in the results are known to exist with no confirmed figure. They are excluded from totals and listed rather than guessed at.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Questions</h2>

  <h3>Is it ever right to form outside the state I work in?</h3>
  <p data-review="legal">
    Sometimes — but the reasons are rarely about cost, and this calculator only measures cost. If you are
    raising outside investment, your investors may require a particular structure and state; that is a
    conversation with them and with a lawyer, not a number on this page.
  </p>

  <h3>What happens if I just do not register in my home state?</h3>
  <p data-review="legal">
    States attach real consequences to it. In California and Texas, for example, an unregistered
    out-of-state entity cannot bring or maintain a lawsuit in that state's courts until it registers —
    while remaining perfectly suable itself. California also assesses a penalty for each taxable year it
    was doing business unregistered. The position is curable, but the cost is delay plus back fees.
  </p>

  <h3>Does a Wyoming or Nevada LLC keep my name off public records?</h3>
  <p data-review="legal">
    Those states do limit what appears in <em>state</em> filings. What we will not tell you is whether
    that amounts to anonymity in 2026, because federal beneficial-ownership reporting is under active
    regulatory development and any firm answer here would age badly. Check the current position with
    FinCEN and the statute rather than trusting a page — including this one.
  </p>

  <h3>Why does the five-year total not include income tax?</h3>
  <p>
    Because income tax is the same in every column, so adding it would inflate every total by an
    identical amount and change no comparison. It is shown separately above the table for exactly that
    reason.
  </p>

  <h3>My state shows a dash instead of a number. Why?</h3>
  <p>
    Because no figure for it has been confirmed from that state's own source. Filing fees change yearly
    and a plausible guess is worse than an admission, so those rows stay empty and the column is marked
    unquantified.
  </p>

  <h2>Related</h2>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    <li><a href="/entity-tax-calculator/">Sole proprietor, S corp or C corp?</a></li>
    <li><a href="/incorporation-tax-calculator/">Delaware franchise tax calculator</a></li>
    <li><a href="/s-corp-tax-calculator/">S-corp election by state</a></li>
    <li><a href="/s-corp-tax-calculator/salary/">What salary to pay yourself</a></li>
    <li><a href="/1099-tax-calculator/">1099 taxes by state</a></li>
  </ul>

  <p class="disclaimer" data-review="legal">
    General information about what states charge, not tax advice — and not legal advice either. Choosing
    where and how to form a business involves legal questions well beyond cost, and an election or filing
    is not always simple to undo. Take advice before filing anything.
  </p>
</Base>
